{"id":"2212.00669","submitter":"Anthony Corso","authors":"Anthony Corso, Yizheng Wang, Markus Zechner, Jef Caers, Mykel J.\n  Kochenderfer","title":"A POMDP Model for Safe Geological Carbon Sequestration","comments":"Accepted at NeurIPS 2022 Workshop on Tackling Climate Change with\n  Machine Learning","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.geo-ph cs.AI","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  Geological carbon capture and sequestration (CCS), where CO$_2$ is stored in\nsubsurface formations, is a promising and scalable approach for reducing global\nemissions. However, if done incorrectly, it may lead to earthquakes and leakage\nof CO$_2$ back to the surface, harming both humans and the environment. These\nrisks are exacerbated by the large amount of uncertainty in the structure of\nthe storage formation. For these reasons, we propose that CCS operations be\nmodeled as a partially observable Markov decision process (POMDP) and decisions\nbe informed using automated planning algorithms. To this end, we develop a\nsimplified model of CCS operations based on a 2D spillpoint analysis that\nretains many of the challenges and safety considerations of the real-world\nproblem. We show how off-the-shelf POMDP solvers outperform expert baselines\nfor safe CCS planning. This POMDP model can be used as a test bed to drive the\ndevelopment of novel decision-making algorithms for CCS operations.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 25 Oct 2022 01:04:13 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-12-02"}
{"id":"2212.07885","submitter":"Brian Jackson","authors":"Brian E. Jackson, Jeong Hun Lee, Kevin Tracy, and Zachary Manchester","title":"Data-Efficient Model Learning for Control with Jacobian-Regularized\n  Dynamic-Mode Decomposition}","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Conference on Robot Learning (CoRL) 2022, Auckland, New Zealand","doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.RO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We present a data-efficient algorithm for learning models for\nmodel-predictive control (MPC). Our approach, Jacobian-Regularized Dynamic-Mode\nDecomposition (JDMD), offers improved sample efficiency over traditional\nKoopman approaches based on Dynamic-Mode Decomposition (DMD) by leveraging\nJacobian information from an approximate prior model of the system, and\nimproved tracking performance over traditional model-based MPC. We demonstrate\nJDMD's ability to quickly learn bilinear Koopman dynamics representations\nacross several realistic examples in simulation, including a perching maneuver\nfor a fixed-wing aircraft with an empirically derived high-fidelity physics\nmodel. In all cases, we show that the models learned by JDMD provide superior\ntracking and generalization performance within a model-predictive control\nframework, even in the presence of significant model mismatch, when compared to\napproximate prior models and models learned by standard Extended DMD (EDMD).\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 25 Oct 2022 12:47:09 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sat, 28 Jan 2023 14:27:23 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-01-31"}
{"id":"2212.13125","submitter":"Ahmet Ilker Topuz Mr.","authors":"Ahmet Ilker Topuz, Madis Kiisk, Andrea Giammanco","title":"Applying triangular correlation of angular deviation in muon scattering\n  tomography for multi-block materials via GEANT4 simulations","comments":"3 figures, 1 table. arXiv admin note: substantial text overlap with\n  arXiv:2112.00376","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.ins-det cond-mat.mtrl-sci","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  The scattering angle due to the target volume can be split into two interior\nangles in the tomographic setups based on the muon scattering, and we call this\nproperty as the triangular correlation where the sum of these two interior\nangles is equal to the scattering angle. In this study, we apply this\ntriangular correlation for a multi-block material configuration that consist of\nconcrete, stainless steel, and uranium. By changing the order of this material\nset, we employ the GEANT4 simulations and we show that the triangular\ncorrelation is valid in the multi-block material setups, thereby providing the\npossibility of supportive information for the coarse prediction of the material\norder in such configurations.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 25 Oct 2022 10:11:26 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 27 Dec 2022 07:40:26 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Thu, 29 Dec 2022 11:37:45 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-01-02"}
